To save data to localStorage in JavaScript, follow these steps:

1. Access the localStorage object using window.localStorage.
2. Set the key-value pair that you want to save by using the setItem() method of the localStorage object. The first argument is the key and the second argument is the value.

Here's an example:

```javascript
// Save data to localStorage
localStorage.setItem("name", "John Doe");
localStorage.setItem("age", 25);
```

To read back the saved data, use the getItem() method of the localStorage object. The first argument is the key whose value you want to retrieve.

Here's an example:

```javascript
// Read data from localStorage
let name = localStorage.getItem("name");
let age = localStorage.getItem("age");

console.log(name); // Output: "John Doe"
console.log(age); // Output: "25"
```

You can also remove an item from localStorage using the removeItem() method, passing the key as an argument. Here's an example:

```javascript
// Remove an item from localStorage
localStorage.removeItem("name");
```

To clear all items from localStorage, use the clear() method of the localStorage object. This will delete all the key-value pairs that are currently stored in localStorage. Here's an example:

```javascript
// Clear all items from localStorage
localStorage.clear();
```
